    Basic Use

    basic-use.Rmd
    library(SimpleFreqs)

    printing

    This package provides a simple way to produce frequency tables. It is built to work both in the console and in knitted documents (i.e. in Rmarkdown or Quarto). It should correctly produce html, pdf, and word output.

    Console 

    freq(iris, Species, markdown = F, plot = F)

Variable: Species
Class: factor
NAs: 0 (0.0%)
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        Species     Freq        %     Cum. Freq     Cum. %
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
         setosa       50     33.3            50       33.3
     versicolor       50     33.3           100       66.7
      virginica       50     33.3           150      100.0
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
          Total      150     100%           150       100%
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    html 

    freq(iris, Species, markdown = T)
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    pdf 

    freq(iris, Species, markdown = T)
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    word 

    freq(iris, Species, markdown = T)
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    It is designed to be used as part of a tidyverse pipeline.

    library(dplyr)

    Hence, the first parameter should be a data frame (or tibble) and the second parameter an unquoted variable from the first parameter.

    freq(iris, Species)
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    or

    iris |>
  freq(Species)
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    Alternatively, you can pass a vector as the first parameter and that will work too.

    freq(iris$Species)
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    or

    freq(iris[["Species"]])
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    Results need not be printed at all. Instead, the results can be assigned to a variable. This will have a class of both “SimpleFreqs_freq” and “data.frame”.

    df <- freq(iris, Species)

class(df)
[1] "SimpleFreqs_freq" "data.frame"

    This object will continue to print as a SimpleFreqs_freqs.

    df <- freq(iris, Species)

df
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    You can remove the “SimpleFreqs_freq” class if needed and the object will print as a regular data.frame.

    df <- freq(iris, Species)

df <- as.data.frame(df)

class(df)
[1] "data.frame"
df
     Species freq proportion cum_freq cum_proportion
1     setosa   50  0.3333333       50      0.3333333
2 versicolor   50  0.3333333      100      0.6666667
3  virginica   50  0.3333333      150      1.0000000

    plots

    By default, a simple bar chart is produced alongside the frequency table.

    freq(iris, Species)
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    Plots can be optionally supressed

    freq(iris, Species, plot = FALSE)
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    #sort By default, a results are sorted in descending order by the frequency of values

    freq(iris, Species, sort = TRUE, plot = FALSE)
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    Alternatively, sorting can be turned off. In that case, results will be sorted by the variables labels. For character variables, it will be alphabetic, for factors it will be by the specified levels of the variable.

    freq(iris, Species, sort = FALSE, plot = FALSE)
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    na.rm

    NAs are, by default, included and treated as any other level of the variable.

    df <- iris |>
  mutate(Species=ifelse(row_number()<10,NA,Species)) |>
    freq(Species, na.rm = FALSE)
df
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    2 50 33.3 50 33.3
    3 50 33.3 100 66.7
    1 41 27.3 141 94.0
    NA 9 6.0 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    Alternatively, nas can be removed. In that case, NAs will not be printed but two relevent attribute will be set on the results. “missing” will include the number of missings removed and missing_removed will be set to TRUE.

    
df <- iris |>
  mutate(Species=ifelse(row_number()<10,NA,Species)) |>
    freq(Species, na.rm = TRUE)
df
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    2 50 35.5 50 35.5
    3 50 35.5 100 70.9
    1 41 29.1 141 100.0
    Total 141 100%

    #markdown

    SimpleFreqs::freq tries to intuit if you are working interactively on the console or are knitting a document. In some cases, you may need to directly specify the type of output you want to display using the markdown= parameter. Set to FALSE when you wish to print for the console.

    freq(iris, Species, markdown = FALSE)

Variable: Species
Class: factor
NAs: 0 (0.0%)
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        Species     Freq        %     Cum. Freq     Cum. %
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
         setosa       50     33.3            50       33.3
     versicolor       50     33.3           100       66.7
      virginica       50     33.3           150      100.0
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
          Total      150     100%           150       100%
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    Set to markdown = TRUE when you wish to include in a knitted document.

    freq(iris, Species, markdown = TRUE)
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    setosa 50 33.3 50 33.3
    versicolor 50 33.3 100 66.7
    virginica 50 33.3 150 100.0
    Total 150 100%

    #wt Results can be optionally weighted by providing a vector of weight values.

    freq(iris, Species,wt=Sepal.Length)
    Species Freq % Cum. Freq Cum. %
    virginica 329.4 37.6 329.4 37.6
    versicolor 296.8 33.9 626.2 71.4
    setosa 250.3 28.6 876.5 100.0
    Total 876 100%
